{"type":"message","id":"fb5c5aa3","parentId":"96c02c3a","timestamp":"2026-04-13T06:59:19.265Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking whether the bootstrap injection worked - whether during /new, the session summary from the previous session was mentioned. The evidence:\n\n1. The user said the summary file `2026-04-13-session-summary.md` exists (751 bytes) but when I try to read it from the workspace root, it doesn't exist\n2. It's actually in the `memory/` directory based on the ls output\n\nBut the real question: did I (in this fresh /new session) spontaneously mention the previous session's topics? Looking at my first greeting - no, I didn't. I just said \"Yo，上次 session...\" based on reading the memory file, not because of bootstrap injection.\n \nSo the bootstrap injection likely didn't fire during /new - I only mentioned the previous session because I explicitly read the memory files myself, not because the bootstrap handler proactively injected the summary into my context. The evidence points to bootstrap not working: the summary file exists but isn't being injected into fresh sessions, which means either the hook didn't fire or the injected content isn't reaching me. A proper test would be to /new again without reading memory files first and see if I spontaneously mention the previous session. I'm realizing the bootstrap handler should theoretically inject content into my context, but if it was working I'd see mention of the previous session in my greeting without needing to read files. Since I don't, and the user confirmed there's no hook execution log, the bootstrap likely isn't firing—which is actually useful diagnostic information. The issue could be that the gateway uses a different event name, or there's a mismatch between what the hook expects and what's actually being emitted.","thinkingSignature":"6b5ae244fb6d02f5c1e63a93d6163cddd6443b8b8366598497e8ce0a79b9290b"},{"type":"text","text":"\n\n没有。上次 /ne