{"type":"message","id":"b5bbdd55","parentId":"039191c3","timestamp":"2026-04-13T07:11:34.130Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"This is the minified/openclaw bootstrap code, and it has references to \"internal hooks\". Let me focus on understanding the actual structure.\n\nLet me look at the self-improvement skill hook more carefully - it's in `/home/ai/.openclaw/skills/self-improving-agent/hooks/openclaw/handler.js` with HOOK.md declaring `events=[\"agent:bootstrap\"]`. This IS a skill-packaged hook. Let me verify if this hook is actually loaded and working.\n\nBut based on my analysis, I think the external hooks in `/home/ai/.openclaw/hooks/` directory are NOT automatically loaded. They need to be either:\n1. Packaged as skills with proper hook metadata\n2. Or registered through some other mechanism\n\nLet me focus on the practical solution: adapting the handler.js to work as a proper hook that gets loaded.\n\nLooking at the self-improving-agent skill, it has:\n- `/home/ai/.openclaw/skills/self-improving-agent/hooks/openclaw/HOOK.md`\n- `/home/ai/.openclaw/skills/self-improving-agent/hooks/openclaw/handler.js`\n\nThe HOOK.md declares it listens to `agent:bootstrap`.\n\nThe handler.js should be the actual implementation.\n\nNow, the key question is: does OpenClaw automatically discover and load hooks from skill directories?\n\nBased on what I've seen, I think the answer is YES - skills that have a `hooks/openclaw/` directory with HOOK.md and handler.js get automatically loaded when the skill is installed.\n\nBut the handler.js in `/home/ai/.openclaw/hooks/` is NOT inside a skill directory, so it doesn't get automatically discovered.\n\nSo the solution is:\n1. Either create a new skill with the memory bootstrap hook\n2. Or modify the existing self-improving-agent skill to include this functionality\n\n\n3. For the built-in hook mechanism, I need to understand how the config.json `hooks.internal.entries` mapping works - these entries seem to reference something specific, possibly the bundled hooks in `/home/ai/.nvm/versions/node/v22.22.1/lib/node_modules/openclaw/dist/bundled/` like `session-memory` and `command-logger`. The external hooks in the workspace directory likely follow a different discovery mechanism.\n\nThe self-improvement skill is actually installed and enabled, so its hook should be running. But looking at the self-improvement hook implementation, it's quite minimal - it just injects a reminder about logging learnings rather than handling the bootstrap event directly. The actual bootstrap hook handling might be in a different skill or need to be registered differently.\n\nI think the best path forward is to move forward with implementation. I'll create a new skill with a proper bootstrap hook that handles the `agent:bootstrap` event and injects memory context. Let me structure this as a clean skill that can be loaded properly.","thinkingSignature":"016d27d14bf1850bfaca968a324119666c9c8e1ad417ede619f88971fc55fbb7"},{"type":"text","text":"好，明白了。`self-improvement` 是个 skill-packaged hook（在 `skills/self-improving-agent/hooks/openclaw/`），而不是靠 `hooks.internal.entries` 加载的。\n\n所以外部 hook 的正确姿势是：**做成 skill 包**。\n\n我来建一个 `memory-bootstrap` skill，专门在 `/new` 时注入记忆上下文：\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_3irv8wbyhtrn_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"mkdir -p /home/ai/.openclaw/skills/memory-bootstrap/hooks/openclaw"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":124888,"output":692,"cacheRead":18601,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":144181,"cost":{"input":0.0374664,"output":0.0008303999999999999,"cacheRead":0.0011160599999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.03941286}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776064262126,"responseId":"062bca0865aad1e59e395bfcc7684c9c"}}
